<DOC><DOCNO> AP890310-0206 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1857EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-10 0332</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0341</SECOND><HEAD>Mild Weather Across Much of Nation</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Gale-force wind and strong waves pounded Florida's northern coaston Friday, but sunny skies brought record high temperatures and mildweather to much of the nation.   Scattered rain Friday fell in the Pacific Northwest.   A flood warning was posted for the John Day River at ServiceCreek, Ore., because warm temperatures had caused a rapid melting ofthe snow. Similar flood warnings were posted in Montana.   An ice jam caused minor lowland flooding at Wilson, Neb., andseveral county roads were closed by flooding in Dodge County, Neb.   Temperatures were unseasonably warm from much of the MississippiValley across the Rockies and the Plateau.   Several cities set high temperature records for the date,including Amarillo, Texas, with 86 degrees; Colorado Springs, Colo.,with 75; Goodland, Kan., with 82; and Pueblo, Colo., with 83.   The low temperature for the nation Friday was 1 degree above zeroat Houlton, Maine.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 29degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 90 degrees at Gage, Okla.   Several beachfront homes were flooded in Fernandina Beach, Fla.,as high tide rose 2 feet above normal. Authorities closed somecoastal roads and chased thousands of people from the sand atDaytona Beach.   Saturday's forecast called for rain over eastern upper Michigan,from western Montana across the Northern Plateau and the northerntwo-thirds of the Pacific Coast.   High temperatures were forecast in the 30s and 40s from NewEngland across inland New York state, the Great Lakes, Minnesota,North Dakota and northeast Montana; in the 50s and 60s fromsoutheast New York state across northern Florida, over the Ohio andTennessee valleys, from eastern Missouri across Iowa and thenorthern Plains, the Rockies, northern Plateau, Great Basin and thenorthern Pacific coast; in the 80s from much of Texas across inlandSouthern California; in the 90s over the desert Southwest; in the70s over the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>